<article>
    <h1>New SUSS cen&#xAD;tre to boost ca&#xAD;pa&#xAD;bil&#xAD;i&#xAD;ties of non-profit sec&#xAD;tor</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201107/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-07"><time>2020-11-07</time></a>
        - <span>SINGAPORE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Goh Yan Han gyan&#xAD;han@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Ef­forts to step up ed­u­ca­tion and re­search for non-profit or­gan­i­sa­tions to help vul­ner­a­ble mem­bers of so­ci­ety will get a boost with the for­ma­tion of the Cen­tre of Ex­cel­lence for So­cial Good at the Sin­ga­pore Univer­sity of So­cial Sci­ences (SUSS).</p>
    <p>The cen­tre will bring to­gether ex­per­tise from the non-profit, public and pri­vate sec­tors in a col­lab­o­ra­tion to en­hance the non-profit sec­tor’s ca­pa­bil­i­ties and prac­tices.</p>
    <p>It will have cour­ses to train and ed­u­cate vol­un­teers and staff of non-prof­its in the ar­eas of dig­i­tal­i­sa­tion, pro­duc­tiv­ity, or­gan­i­sa­tion ef­fec­tive­ness and gov­er­nance.</p>
    <p>The cen­tre will also con­duct re­search to help in­form poli­cies and di­rect ef­fort where it is needed, and iden­tify where part­ner­ships and col­lab­o­ra­tions will be most ef­fec­tive.</p>
    <p>To launch the new cen­tre, the univer­sity signed a mem­o­ran­dum of un­der­stand­ing with the SG Cares Of­fice, a unit un­der the Min­istry of Cul­ture, Com­mu­nity and Youth (MCCY), yes­ter­day.</p>
    <p>The SG Cares Of­fice will pro­vide the new cen­tre with sup­port and re­sources to form part­ner­ships be­tween the pri­vate and peo­ple sec­tors, pro­mote ground-up ini­tia­tives and en­cour­age vol­un­teerism.</p>
    <p>The mem­o­ran­dum was signed by MCCY deputy sec­re­tary Ang Hak Seng and SUSS provost Tsui Kai Chong, and wit­nessed by Cul­ture, Com­mu­nity and Youth Min­is­ter Ed­win Tong and SUSS pres­i­dent Cheong Hee Kiat.</p>
    <p>Said Mr Tong: “In times of change and un­cer­tainty, there is a press­ing need for non-prof­its to im­prove ca­pa­bil­i­ties. In do­ing so, non-prof­its can bet­ter en­gage givers, adapt the modal­ity of vol­un­teer­ing pro­grammes, and also de­liver ser­vices that best suit the needs of vul­ner­a­ble groups.</p>
    <p>“The launch of the Cen­tre of Ex­cel­lence for So­cial Good is in­deed timely. It is also cru­cial in de­vel­op­ing ca­pa­bil­i­ties in the non-profit sec­tor.”</p>
    <p>With non-profit or­gan­i­sa­tions hav­ing stronger ca­pa­bil­i­ties, the en­tire sec­tor will be­come more trusted and vi­brant, and be able to ef­fec­tively part­ner one an­other to ad­dress needs in a more co­or­di­nated and sys­tem­atic way, he added.</p>
    <p>Pro­fes­sor Cheong said: “For SUSS, the ad­di­tion of this cen­tre will bring so­cial sec­tor net­works to us, ex­tend our reach into the com­mu­nity, and strengthen our com­mit­ment of pro­mot­ing en­gage­ments for so­cial good.”</p>
    <p>He added: “There are calls for in­creas­ing part­ner­ships and co­or­di­na­tion to pro­vide ser­vices on the ground. But the col­lab­o­ra­tive fo­cus can also be in­creased in ed­u­ca­tion and train­ing, ap­plied re­search, ad­vo­cacy and in­form­ing, and strate­gic col­lab­o­ra­tion.”</p>
    <p>One non-profit or­gan­i­sa­tion that hopes to ben­e­fit from the new cen­tre is the Lions Home For The El­ders, which aims to tap SUSS’ ex­per­tise for its clin­i­cal staff to fur­ther their ed­u­ca­tion and im­prove their pro­fes­sional ca­pa­bil­i­ties.</p>
    <p>Its board chair­man Henre Tan said the home can pro­vide data to SUSS for re­search in el­der­care, which the cen­tre can an­a­lyse.</p>
    <p>The home could use the find­ings to re­view its pro­cesses, he added.</p>

